Lets move away from the shiny IPO objects and $TSLA and instead look at the weakness in former large cap leaders ($AMZN, $GM, $WMT, etc.) - this should begin to give market pundits some pause...

Its not his bias that many find objectionable, it is the lack of journalistic quality which leads him to wander into unrelated stuff like how much $ is a hedge hogger earning and how big is his residence, political dogma, who he is betting on in football over the weekend, etc.

Kernan has spent six years on his @cnbc bully pulpit attacking me - and I have been helpless to respond. But the broadening impact of social media (e.g. Twitter) means I can defend myself quite effectively from his ad hominem B.S. in real time. @SquawkCNBC

Doing homework and preparing for an interview are an anathema to him. There is no value added when launching simplistic questions to guests aimed at allowing them to recite bullet points and deferring the subject of reward v risk and teh concept of "margin of safety."

One would think that Kernan would ask his guest the simple question of the merit of buying Marriott's shares which have risen from under $40 to $135. Nope. Crickets. Just soft ball questions responded with memorized bullet points. Same old same old. @SquawkCNBC
Enjoy the weekend all. Trade and invest well. Be safe.
